OOPS is an utility that provides a convenient method of correcting a  mistyped
command  without  retyping  the  entire  command.   (The command that is to be
corrected must still be on the screen for OOPS to be used.)

OOPS can be also used to change the filenames or options of previous commands.
This  is useful when performing repeated operations on different files or with
different parameters.

To use OOPS, simply type:       OOPS [ENTER]
If OOPS is installed as the Immediate Execution Program (IEP),  then  use  the
command:        * [ENTER]

Using the [UP-ARROW] or [DOWN-ARROW] keys, move the cursor to  the  line  that
you  want  to  edit.  When the cursor is over the desired line, press [ENTER],
[F3], or [.].  ([ENTER] clears the screen below the line to be  edited,  while
[F3] and [.] do not.)

Once a line has been selected, it may be edited by using  the  same  functions
that  are  available in the EDIT command in BASIC.  These are described in de-
tail with examples in the TRSDOS 6 Disk System  Owners  Manual.   This  manual
should  have  come with your system, but can be ordered from Radio Shack, #26-
0316.  A quick summary of each command is provided below.

[ENTER]         Submits the command to the  operating  system  command  inter-
                preter.

[BREAK]         Exits OOPS without performing any operation.  If OOPS is in  a
                special  mode,  the first [BREAK] exits the special mode and a
                second [BREAK] exits OOPS.  You can tell if you are in a  spe-
                cial  mode  by looking at the bottom-right part of the screen.
                For example, if you see the word

[I]             Enter insertion mode.  Characters will be inserted in front of
                the  character  currently  under the cursor.  Pressing [ENTER]
                submits the command to the system.   Pressing  [F3],  [BREAK],
                [SHIFT][UP-ARROW]  or any other control character exits insert
                mode.

[X]             Enters insertion mode, but positions the cursor at the end  of
                the line.  See the [I] command for more information.

[H] or [T]      Deletes all characters to the right of the cursor, and  enters
                insert mode.  See the [I] command.

[S]             Searches for the next character that is entered and moves  the
                cursor  to  that position.  If the character that is specified
                is not found to the right of the cursor, the cursor  is  moved
                to the end of the line. The search is case-sensitive; in other
                words, if you search for the letter 't', the uppercase  letter
                'T' will not be found by the search.

[C]             Changes the character under the cursor to the  next  character
                that is typed.  The cursor moves one position to the right.

[D]             Deletes the character under the cursor and moves the  text  on
                the right of the cursor to the left to fill the hole.

                                   Page  1






[K]             Searches for the next character that is typed and deletes  the
                characters  between  the  current  position  and  the  search-
                character.  If the character is not found, no  characters  are
                deleted.  If the character to search for is [ENTER], the char-
                acters to the right of the cursor are deleted.   As  with  the
                Search command, the search is case-sensitive.

[0] thru [9]    The numeric keys allow you to specify a repetition count.  For
                example,  pressing [5][S][X] causes OOPS to move the cursor to
                the 5th occurrence of the letter 'x'.  A repeat value  from  2
                to  79  can  be entered.  As the digits are entered, they will
                appear in the status area at the bottom of  the  screen.   The
                following commands can be repeated:
                        [S]             Search Mode
                        [K]             Kill (Delete String) Mode
                        [D]             Delete Mode
                        [C]             Change Mode
                        [SPACE]         Move Cursor Right
                        [RIGHT-ARROW]   Move Cursor Right
                        [LEFT-ARROW]    Move Cursor Left
                In the case of the change command ([C]), the  count  remaining
                in  the repeat is displayed at the bottom of the screen as the
                changes are made.

                Commands not listed above reset the repeat count  to  zero  if
                one was specified.

                If the repeat rate causes the command to be performed  an  in-
                valid  number of times, the command is performed until the end
                of the line is reached, then the  remaining  repeat  count  is
                discarded.   For  example,  attempting to delete 90 characters
                will only delete the number of characters on the line.

[.]             Allows one or both digits of the repeat value  to  be  erased.
                This  can  be done until an edit command is entered.  The last
                digit (ones' digit) is the first removed.

[U]             Aborts all changes made so far and restores the  line  to  its
                original state.  The cursor is positioned to column 1.

[F1] or [L]     Moves the cursor to the column 1.

[F2]            Moves the cursor one column past the  last  character  on  the
                line.

[LEFT-ARROW]    Moves the cursor one position to the left.

[RIGHT-ARROW]   Moves the cursor one position to the right.

[F3]            Exits any special mode OOPS may be in.  These are displayed at
                the  bottom-right  of the screen.  If OOPS is not in a special
                mode when [F3] is pressed, it is ignored.







