Technical Information

OOPS runs in the library overlay area and does not disturb memory below 0x2600
or above 0x2FFF on the Model 4.  The Model III version loads at 0x5800.

Programs may invoke OOPS, but OOPS will not return control to them.

The display state is not altered by OOPS;  therefore, if  the  cursor  is  off
when  OOPS is executed, it will not be very usable.  Reverse video text cannot
be edited reliably, and may not be recognized by the command interpreter.

The Model 4/4P/4D version of OOPS must be used with  LS-DOS  6.2.0  or  later.
The Model III version of OOPS works with LDOS 5.x and TRSDOS 1.x.

To install OOPS as the Immediate Execution Program (IEP) in  LS-DOS,  use  the
command:

        COPY OOPS/CMD SYS13/SYS:0 (C=N)

Once done, OOPS can be invoked by typing:       * [ENTER]

OOPS utilizes the @VDCTL SVC in LS-DOS or a scan of video memory in Model  III
mode  to  read old commands from the screen, thus allowing it to edit commands
other than the last command entered.  The command must still be on the  screen
for  OOPS  to  be  able  to  access it.  The edited command is supplied to the
operating system via the @CMNDI call or SVC.

